# A Mobile App Is Coming — Build Client-Agnostic

BumBumSafe currently has a web client, but a native **mobile app (iOS/Android)
is planned**. Treat the web as *one of several* clients. When adding any feature
or API, keep the future mobile app in mind.

## Always do

- **Put shared logic + data behind the Go API** (`bumbumpeace-api`), not only in
  the Next.js layer. Mobile cannot reuse Server Components / Route Handlers — it
  needs plain HTTP/JSON. Business rules (budget math, filtering, auth,
  settings) should be reachable via the API so every client shares them.
- **Keep the API client-agnostic**: clean JSON, no web-only assumptions
  (no HTML, no cookies-only flows that mobile can't use easily — prefer
  token-based auth that works for web *and* mobile).
- **Version the API** (e.g. `/v1/...`) so mobile can depend on a stable contract
  across web releases.
- **Design auth to work cross-platform** (Cognito + JWT validated by
  `go-jwt-middleware`); avoid web-only session assumptions.
- **Web-specific code stays in the web app**; don't bake presentation concerns
  into API responses.

## When proposing features

- State briefly how it works for **both web and a future mobile client**
  (e.g. "expose via `GET /v1/cities`; web and mobile both consume it").
- If something is intentionally web-only (SEO page, marketing), call it out.

## Avoid

- Putting durable business logic *only* in Next.js where mobile can't reach it.
- API responses tailored to the web DOM.
- Auth/session designs that don't translate to native apps.

> Not every change needs mobile work now — just don't make choices that block a
> mobile app later.
